04973nam a22007695i 9780674056749DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979683591  a97806740567497 a10.4159/97806740567492doi  a(DE-B1597)457718  a(OCoLC)779172986  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJC67b.N45 2010eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.01/12221 aNelson, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hebrew Republic :bJewish Sources and the Transformation of European Political Thought /cEric Nelson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. “Talmudical Commonwealthsmen” and the Rise of Republican Exclusivism -- tChapter 2. “For the Land Is Mine”: The Hebrew Commonwealth and the Rise of Redistribution -- tChapter 3. Hebrew Theocracy and the Rise of Toleration -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccording to a commonplace narrative, the rise of modern political thought in the West resulted from secularization—the exclusion of religious arguments from political discourse. But in this pathbreaking work Eric Nelson argues that this familiar story is wrong. Instead, he contends, political thought in early-modern Europe became less, not more, secular with time, and it was the Christian encounter with Hebrew sources that provoked this radical transformation. During the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, Christian scholars began to regard the Hebrew Bible as a political constitution designed by God for the children of Israel. Newly available rabbinic materials became authoritative guides to the institutions and practices of the perfect republic. This thinking resulted in a sweeping reorientation of political commitments. In the book’s central chapters Nelson identifies three transformative claims introduced into European political theory by the Hebrew revival: the argument that republics are the only legitimate regimes; the idea that the state should coercively maintain an egalitarian distribution of property; and the belief that a godly republic would tolerate religious diversity. One major consequence of Nelson’s work is that the revolutionary politics of John Milton, James Harrington, and Thomas Hobbes appear in a brand-new light. Nelson demonstrates that central features of modern political thought emerged from an attempt to emulate a constitution designed by God. This paradox, a reminder that while we may live in a secular age, we owe our politics to an age of religious fervor, in turn illuminates fault lines in contemporary political discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewsxPolitics and governmentxTo 70 A.D. 0aJewsxPolitics and governmentyTo 70 A.D. 0aJudaism and politicsxHistory of doctrines. 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryxEurope. 0aPolitical sciencezEuropexHistory. 0aPolitics in rabbinical literature. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067405674940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674056749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674056749.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA